Note:
Syscall Sequence Generator - Inline Syscall Code Generation

Generates optimized inline assembly sequences for syscall invocation on each
target platform. The generator translates abstract syscall requests into
platform-specific instruction sequences that load the syscall number into the
appropriate register, set up argument registers, invoke the syscall instruction,
and handle the return value and error checking.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Generate inline assembly sequences for syscall invocation per platform
- Optimize generated syscall sequences (register reuse, dead store elimination)
- Handle platform-specific error checking (carry flag, negative return, CR0.SO)
- Support both direct syscall emission and function-wrapped syscall generation

This file is essential because:
- The compiler needs to emit platform-specific syscall sequences inline
- Each architecture has different register assignments and syscall instructions
- Error handling differs across platforms (carry flag vs negative return vs CR0.SO)
- Optimization of syscall sequences reduces code size and improves performance

Dependencies:
- platform_interface for SyscallConvention and PlatformInfo types
- syscall_registry for syscall lookup
- machine_code_interface for assembly instruction encoding
- memory layout for buffer allocation
- list for instruction sequence management
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Instruction Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Each generated instruction in the syscall sequence has a type that describes
what kind of operation it performs. This enables the optimizer to reason about
the instruction stream without parsing assembly text.
@End Reasoning

Constant INST_MOVE_IMM as Integer is 1      Note: Load immediate value into register
Constant INST_MOVE_REG as Integer is 2      Note: Move value between registers
Constant INST_SYSCALL as Integer is 3       Note: Execute syscall instruction
Constant INST_COMPARE as Integer is 4       Note: Compare for error checking
Constant INST_BRANCH as Integer is 5        Note: Conditional branch (error handling)
Constant INST_NEGATE as Integer is 6        Note: Negate register (for errno extraction)
Constant INST_TEST_CARRY as Integer is 7    Note: Test carry flag (BSD error handling)
Constant INST_TEST_CR0_SO as Integer is 8   Note: Test CR0.SO bit (PowerPC error handling)
Constant INST_LOAD_STACK as Integer is 9    Note: Load argument from stack (MIPS o32)
Constant INST_STORE_STACK as Integer is 10  Note: Store argument to stack (MIPS o32)

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Instruction Node Type
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Each node in the instruction sequence represents a single assembly operation
with its operands. The dst_reg and src_reg fields hold register IDs, and the
immediate field holds literal values (syscall numbers, argument values, etc.).

The type field uses one of the INST_* constants above to classify the instruction
for optimization purposes.
@End Reasoning

Type called "SyscallInstruction":
    inst_type as Integer       Note: INST_* constant identifying the instruction kind
    dst_reg as Integer         Note: Destination register ID (-1 if not applicable)
    src_reg as Integer         Note: Source register ID (-1 if not applicable)
    immediate as Integer       Note: Immediate value (syscall number, offset, etc.)
    label as Integer           Note: Pointer to label string (for branches, 0 if none)
End Type

Note: Size: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes per SyscallInstruction

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Instruction Creation Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_instruction" that takes inst_type as Integer, dst_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocates and initializes a SyscallInstruction node
    Note: Returns pointer to instruction, or 0 on allocation failure

    Let inst be Layout.allocate(40)
    If inst is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(inst, 0, inst_type)
    __store(inst, 8, dst_reg)
    __store(inst, 16, src_reg)
    __store(inst, 24, immediate)
    __store(inst, 32, 0)

    Return inst
End Process

Process called "create_instruction_with_label" that takes inst_type as Integer, dst_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, immediate as Integer, label as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocates a SyscallInstruction with an associated label string
    Note: Returns pointer to instruction, or 0 on allocation failure

    Let inst be create_instruction(inst_type, dst_reg, src_reg, immediate)
    If inst is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(inst, 32, label)

    Return inst
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Syscall Inline Sequence Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
generate_syscall_inline produces the full instruction sequence needed to invoke
a specific syscall on a given platform. The sequence consists of:

1. Loading the syscall number into the number register (with any platform offset)
2. Setting up each argument in the correct register (or stack slot for MIPS o32)
3. Executing the platform-specific syscall instruction
4. Handling error detection (carry flag, negative return, or CR0.SO)

The function takes:
- platform_id: Identifies the target platform
- convention: Pre-fetched SyscallConvention for the platform
- syscall_number: The raw syscall number for this platform
- arg_values: List of argument values (as register IDs or immediates)
- arg_count: Number of arguments to pass

It returns a List of SyscallInstruction pointers representing the complete
inline sequence, or 0 on failure. The caller is responsible for translating
these instructions into actual assembly text or machine code bytes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "generate_syscall_inline" that takes platform_id as Integer, convention as Integer, syscall_number as Integer, arg_values as Integer, arg_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generates an inline syscall instruction sequence for the given platform
    Note: Returns a list of SyscallInstruction pointers, or 0 on failure

    If convention is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create the instruction sequence list
    Let sequence be List.list_create(16)
    If sequence is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1: Load syscall number into the number register
    Note: Apply any platform-specific offset (e.g., 0x2000000 for Darwin)
    Let number_reg be PlatformInterface.convention_get_number_register(convention)
    Let offset be PlatformInterface.convention_get_syscall_offset(convention)
    Let effective_number be syscall_number plus offset

    Let inst_number be create_instruction(INST_MOVE_IMM, number_reg, -1, effective_number)
    If inst_number is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    List.list_append(sequence, inst_number)

    Note: Step 2: Load each argument into the correct register
    Note: For most platforms (x86_64, ARM64, RISC-V, PowerPC), all 6 args go in registers
    Note: For MIPS32 o32, only 4 args go in registers; args 5-6 go on stack
    Let arg_idx be 0
    While arg_idx is less than arg_count:
        If arg_idx is less than 6:
            Let arg_reg be PlatformInterface.convention_get_arg_register(convention, arg_idx)

            Note: Check if this is a stack argument (register ID 0 for MIPS o32 args 5-6)
            If arg_reg is 0:
                If arg_idx is greater than or equal to 4:
                    Note: MIPS o32 stack argument: store at stack offset
                    Note: Stack args start at offset 16 from $sp (after 4 saved arg slots)
                    Let stack_offset be 16 plus ((arg_idx minus 4) multiplied by 4)
                    Let arg_val be 0
                    If arg_values is not 0:
                        Set arg_val to List.list_get(arg_values, arg_idx)
                    End If
                    Let inst_stack be create_instruction(INST_STORE_STACK, -1, arg_val, stack_offset)
                    If inst_stack is not 0:
                        List.list_append(sequence, inst_stack)
                    End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Register argument: move value into the argument register
                Let arg_val be 0
                If arg_values is not 0:
                    Set arg_val to List.list_get(arg_values, arg_idx)
                End If

                Note: If the argument value is already in the correct register, skip the move
                If arg_val is not arg_reg:
                    Let inst_arg be create_instruction(INST_MOVE_REG, arg_reg, arg_val, 0)
                    If inst_arg is not 0:
                        List.list_append(sequence, inst_arg)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set arg_idx to arg_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 3: Execute the syscall instruction
    Let inst_syscall be create_instruction(INST_SYSCALL, -1, -1, platform_id)
    If inst_syscall is not 0:
        List.list_append(sequence, inst_syscall)
    End If

    Note: Step 4: Error handling
    Note: Different platforms signal errors differently:
    Note: - Linux x86_64/ARM64/RISC-V: negative return value in result register
    Note: - BSD x86_64 / Darwin: carry flag set, result register has errno
    Note: - PowerPC: CR0.SO bit set, result register has errno
    Note: - MIPS: $a3 non-zero, $v0 has errno

    Let uses_carry be PlatformInterface.convention_uses_carry_error(convention)

    If uses_carry is 1:
        Note: BSD/Darwin/PowerPC: test carry/CR0.SO flag
        If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC:
            Note: PowerPC uses CR0.SO bit
            Let inst_test be create_instruction(INST_TEST_CR0_SO, -1, -1, 0)
            If inst_test is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_test)
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: BSD/Darwin: test carry flag
            Let inst_test be create_instruction(INST_TEST_CARRY, -1, -1, 0)
            If inst_test is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_test)
            End If
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: Linux-style: check if return value is negative (indicating -errno)
        Let return_reg be PlatformInterface.convention_get_return_register(convention)

        Note: Check for MIPS error handling (error flag in separate register)
        Let error_reg be __load(convention, 32)
        If error_reg is not 0:
            If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32:
                Note: MIPS: test $a3 for error
                Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, error_reg, -1, 0)
                If inst_cmp is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
                End If
            End If
            If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64:
                Note: MIPS64: test $a3 for error
                Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, error_reg, -1, 0)
                If inst_cmp is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Standard Linux: compare return value against -4096
            Note: If return value > -4096 (unsigned), it is a negated errno
            Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, return_reg, -1, -4096)
            If inst_cmp is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return sequence
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Syscall Sequence Optimization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
optimize_syscall_sequence performs peephole optimizations on a generated syscall
instruction sequence. The optimizations include:

1. Dead move elimination: If a register-to-register move has src == dst, remove it.
   This occurs when the argument value is already in the correct register.

2. Immediate folding: If a move-immediate is followed by a register move into
   the same destination, fold them into a single move-immediate.

3. Redundant load elimination: If the same value is loaded into the same register
   twice in sequence, remove the duplicate.

These optimizations reduce code size without changing semantics. The function
modifies the sequence in-place and returns the number of instructions removed.
@End Reasoning

Process called "optimize_syscall_sequence" that takes sequence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Optimizes a syscall instruction sequence in-place
    Note: Returns the number of instructions removed, or -1 on error

    If sequence is 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let length be List.list_length(sequence)
    If length is less than or equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let removed be 0
    Let idx be 0

    Note: Pass 1: Eliminate self-moves (move reg to itself)
    While idx is less than length:
        Let inst be List.list_get(sequence, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            Let inst_type be __load(inst, 0)
            If inst_type is INST_MOVE_REG:
                Let dst be __load(inst, 8)
                Let src be __load(inst, 16)
                If dst is src:
                    Note: Self-move detected: mark for removal by setting type to 0
                    __store(inst, 0, 0)
                    Set removed to removed plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Pass 2: Eliminate redundant consecutive loads to the same register
    Note: If instruction N loads register R with value V, and instruction N+1
    Note: also loads register R with value V, remove instruction N
    Set idx to 0
    While idx is less than length minus 1:
        Let inst_a be List.list_get(sequence, idx)
        Let inst_b be List.list_get(sequence, idx plus 1)

        If inst_a is not 0:
            If inst_b is not 0:
                Let type_a be __load(inst_a, 0)
                Let type_b be __load(inst_b, 0)

                Note: Check for consecutive identical move-immediate instructions
                If type_a is INST_MOVE_IMM:
                    If type_b is INST_MOVE_IMM:
                        Let dst_a be __load(inst_a, 8)
                        Let dst_b be __load(inst_b, 8)
                        Let imm_a be __load(inst_a, 24)
                        Let imm_b be __load(inst_b, 24)

                        If dst_a is dst_b:
                            If imm_a is imm_b:
                                Note: Duplicate load: mark the first one for removal
                                __store(inst_a, 0, 0)
                                Set removed to removed plus 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Check for move-immediate followed by overwriting move-register
                Note: to the same destination (the immediate is wasted)
                If type_a is INST_MOVE_IMM:
                    If type_b is INST_MOVE_REG:
                        Let dst_a be __load(inst_a, 8)
                        Let dst_b be __load(inst_b, 8)

                        If dst_a is dst_b:
                            Note: The immediate load is overwritten: mark for removal
                            __store(inst_a, 0, 0)
                            Set removed to removed plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Pass 3: Compact the sequence by removing marked instructions (type == 0)
    If removed is greater than 0:
        Let write_idx be 0
        Let read_idx be 0
        While read_idx is less than length:
            Let inst be List.list_get(sequence, read_idx)
            If inst is not 0:
                Let inst_type be __load(inst, 0)
                If inst_type is not 0:
                    Note: Keep this instruction
                    If write_idx is not read_idx:
                        List.list_set(sequence, write_idx, inst)
                    End If
                    Set write_idx to write_idx plus 1
                End If
            End If
            Set read_idx to read_idx plus 1
        End While

        Note: Truncate the list to the new length
        Note: Set remaining slots to 0
        While write_idx is less than length:
            List.list_set(sequence, write_idx, 0)
            Set write_idx to write_idx plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return removed
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Standalone Error Check Sequence Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
generate_error_check_sequence produces the error-checking instruction subsequence
that should follow a syscall instruction. This is extracted as a standalone function
so that callers who build their own instruction sequences (rather than using
generate_syscall_inline) can append proper error detection.

The error-checking strategy differs by platform:
- Linux x86_64/ARM64/RISC-V/ARM32: The return value is a negated errno if the
  unsigned value exceeds (MAX - 4096). We emit INST_COMPARE against -4096.
- BSD/Darwin x86_64/ARM64: The carry flag is set on error. We emit INST_TEST_CARRY.
- Linux PowerPC: The CR0.SO (summary overflow) bit is set on error. We emit
  INST_TEST_CR0_SO.
- Linux MIPS32/MIPS64: A separate error register ($a3) is nonzero on error.
  We emit INST_COMPARE on that register against 0.

The function returns a List of SyscallInstruction pointers representing the error
check sequence, or 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

Process called "generate_error_check_sequence" that takes platform_id as Integer, convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generates a standalone error-checking instruction sequence for the given platform
    Note: Returns a list of SyscallInstruction pointers, or 0 on failure

    If convention is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sequence be List.list_create(4)
    If sequence is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let uses_carry be PlatformInterface.convention_uses_carry_error(convention)

    If uses_carry is 1:
        Note: BSD/Darwin/PowerPC: test carry flag or CR0.SO
        If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC:
            Note: PowerPC signals errors via the CR0.SO (summary overflow) bit
            Let inst_test be create_instruction(INST_TEST_CR0_SO, -1, -1, 0)
            If inst_test is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_test)
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: BSD and Darwin platforms signal errors via the CPU carry flag
            Let inst_test be create_instruction(INST_TEST_CARRY, -1, -1, 0)
            If inst_test is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_test)
            End If
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: Non-carry-flag platforms: check return value or dedicated error register
        Let return_reg be PlatformInterface.convention_get_return_register(convention)

        Note: Check for MIPS-style error handling with a dedicated error register
        Note: SyscallConvention offset 32 is the error_register field
        Let error_reg be __load(convention, 32)

        If error_reg is not 0:
            Note: MIPS platforms: $a3 is nonzero when the syscall failed
            If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32:
                Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, error_reg, -1, 0)
                If inst_cmp is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
                End If
                Note: Branch to error handler if error register is nonzero
                Let inst_branch be create_instruction_with_label(INST_BRANCH, -1, -1, 1, ".Lsyscall_error")
                If inst_branch is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_branch)
                End If
            End If
            If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64:
                Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, error_reg, -1, 0)
                If inst_cmp is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
                End If
                Let inst_branch be create_instruction_with_label(INST_BRANCH, -1, -1, 1, ".Lsyscall_error")
                If inst_branch is not 0:
                    List.list_append(sequence, inst_branch)
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Standard Linux: compare return value against -4096
            Note: If the unsigned return value is above (2^64 - 4096), it represents -errno
            Let inst_cmp be create_instruction(INST_COMPARE, return_reg, -1, -4096)
            If inst_cmp is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_cmp)
            End If
            Note: Branch to error handler if comparison indicates error
            Let inst_branch be create_instruction_with_label(INST_BRANCH, -1, -1, 1, ".Lsyscall_error")
            If inst_branch is not 0:
                List.list_append(sequence, inst_branch)
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return sequence
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Instruction Sequence to Assembly Text Emission
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
emit_sequence_as_assembly converts a list of SyscallInstruction nodes into actual
assembly text and appends it to the given AssemblyOutput's .text section. Each
instruction type maps to a specific assembly pattern depending on the target
architecture (derived from platform_id).

Register IDs are translated to architecture-specific register name strings using
a helper lookup. The function handles all INST_* types:

- INST_MOVE_IMM: Load an immediate value into a register
- INST_MOVE_REG: Move a value between two registers
- INST_SYSCALL: Emit the platform's syscall instruction (syscall/svc/swi/ecall/sc)
- INST_COMPARE: Compare a register against an immediate value
- INST_BRANCH: Conditional branch to a label
- INST_NEGATE: Negate a register value (for errno extraction)
- INST_TEST_CARRY: Test the carry flag (BSD error detection)
- INST_TEST_CR0_SO: Test the PowerPC CR0.SO bit
- INST_LOAD_STACK: Load a value from a stack offset
- INST_STORE_STACK: Store a value to a stack offset

The function returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_register_name_for_platform" that takes platform_id as Integer, reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translates a numeric register ID to the architecture-specific register name string
    Note: Returns pointer to register name string, or 0 if unknown

    Note: Determine architecture from platform_id
    Note: x86_64 platforms: 1 (Linux), 4 (Darwin), 6 (Windows), 8 (FreeBSD), 10 (OpenBSD), 12 (NetBSD)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_DARWIN_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WINDOWS_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_FREEBSD_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_OPENBSD_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_NETBSD_X86_64:
        Return get_x86_64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Note: AArch64 platforms: 2 (Linux), 5 (Darwin), 7 (Windows), 9 (FreeBSD), 11 (OpenBSD), 13 (NetBSD)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_DARWIN_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WINDOWS_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_FREEBSD_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_OPENBSD_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_NETBSD_ARM64:
        Return get_aarch64_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Note: ARM32: 3 (Linux)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM32:
        Return get_arm32_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Note: RISC-V: 17 (RV32), 18 (RV64)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV32:
        Return get_riscv_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV64:
        Return get_riscv_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Note: MIPS: 14 (MIPS32), 15 (MIPS64)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32:
        Return get_mips_register_name(reg_id)
    End If
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64:
        Return get_mips_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Note: PowerPC: 16 (Linux)
    If platform_id is PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC:
        Return get_powerpc_register_name(reg_id)
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_x86_64_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns x86_64 register name for the given register ID
    Note: Register IDs follow the SyscallConvention assignments:
    Note: 0=RAX, 1=RBX, 2=RCX, 3=RDX, 4=RSI, 5=RDI, 6=RSP, 7=RBP
    Note: 8=R8, 9=R9, 10=R10, 11=R11, 12=R12, 13=R13, 14=R14, 15=R15
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "%rax"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "%rbx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "%rcx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "%rdx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "%rsi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "%rdi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "%rsp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "%rbp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "%r8"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "%r9"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "%r10"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "%r11"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "%r12"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "%r13"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "%r14"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "%r15"
    End If
    Return "%rax"
End Process

Process called "get_aarch64_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns AArch64 register name for the given register ID
    Note: Register IDs 0-30 map to x0-x30, 31 is SP
    If reg_id is less than 0:
        Return "x0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "x0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "x1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "x2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "x3"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "x4"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "x5"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "x6"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "x7"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "x8"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "x9"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "x10"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "x11"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "x12"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "x13"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "x14"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "x15"
    End If
    If reg_id is 16:
        Return "x16"
    End If
    If reg_id is 17:
        Return "x17"
    End If
    If reg_id is 18:
        Return "x18"
    End If
    If reg_id is 19:
        Return "x19"
    End If
    If reg_id is 20:
        Return "x20"
    End If
    If reg_id is 29:
        Return "x29"
    End If
    If reg_id is 30:
        Return "x30"
    End If
    If reg_id is 31:
        Return "sp"
    End If
    Return "x0"
End Process

Process called "get_arm32_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns ARM32 register name for the given register ID
    Note: Register IDs 0-15 map to r0-r15
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "r0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "r1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "r2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "r3"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "r4"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "r5"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "r6"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "r7"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "r8"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "r9"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "r10"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "r11"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "r12"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "sp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "lr"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "pc"
    End If
    Return "r0"
End Process

Process called "get_riscv_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns RISC-V ABI register name for the given register ID
    Note: Uses ABI names: a0-a7, t0-t6, s0-s11, etc.
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "zero"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "ra"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "sp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "gp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "tp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "t0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "t1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "t2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "s0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "s1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "a0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "a1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "a2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "a3"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "a4"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "a5"
    End If
    If reg_id is 16:
        Return "a6"
    End If
    If reg_id is 17:
        Return "a7"
    End If
    Return "a0"
End Process

Process called "get_mips_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns MIPS register name for the given register ID
    Note: Standard MIPS register numbering with ABI names
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "$zero"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "$at"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "$v0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "$v1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "$a0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "$a1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "$a2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "$a3"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "$t0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "$t1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 29:
        Return "$sp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 31:
        Return "$ra"
    End If
    Return "$v0"
End Process

Process called "get_powerpc_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns PowerPC register name for the given register ID
    Note: Register IDs 0-31 map to r0-r31
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "r0"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "r1"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "r2"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "r3"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "r4"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "r5"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "r6"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "r7"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "r8"
